We are told by the Norse writers that Moray, with a great part of the North of Scotland, was occasionally under Norwegian rule, and independent of the Crown of Scotland, for the greater part of two cen- turies. Thorstein the Red, Sigurd, and Thorfin, ruled either with avowed inde- pendence, or with only a nominal acknowledgment of the sovereignty of the Scottish monarchs, from the beginning of the tenth to the middle of the eleventh century. About the termination of their sway, the feeble light of our own history begins to dawn, and presents us with a succession of native lords of Moray, whose names only are preserved, but who appear to have been in some way connected with the reigning family of Scotland, and to have drawn their followers into frequent ruinous insurrec- tions, either in maintaining their claims to the throne, or in resisting the authority of the ruling sovereign.¹ These were at length terminated only by the expulsion of the
